data.body:
I'm using your TransformControls in the level editor of my game engine but had to modify some things to get it working properly. The reason for this is because I'm using WebWorkers pretty excessively and there is no `document`, let alone mouse events directly available in a worker context.

![](https://lekker.sexy/materia4.png)

So I'm wondering if it would be possible for you to separate the logic that handles mouse events from the  event listeners. Basically what I'm asking is that you change things like:
```js
function onPointerHover(event) {
    if ( scope.object === undefined || scope.dragging === true || ( event.button !== undefined && event.button !== 0 ) ) return;
```
to simply:
```js
function onPointerHover(mouseX, mouseY) {
    if ( scope.object === undefined || scope.dragging === true ) return;
    // ... do stuff here.
```
And do the logic to check which button is pressed etc, somewhere in the same segment where you also bind the event listeners to the mouse events. This way, if people use THREE in a worker context like myself, it takes a lot less effort hacking in the code to get this working properly.

If you find this too much hassle, I'm happy to file a PR once this one gets merged.

**EDIT** : I already got it working and it ook me less than 5 minutes 😄 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/567518/40880302-66205e44-66ae-11e8-9eaa-9bc8c2714c9b.png)

Secret gist of what I did : https://gist.github.com/haroldiedema/8b8aae3e05c396f797fc1244725b26b9 
I haven't tested the DOM (non-worker) version, but I assume it works.

P.S don't mind the code style. This was just a "quick hack".


---

Looks good! 👍 

If it were completely up to me, I would instead create a separate "controller" that you would optionally "inject" into the constructor of the entire class though. One works for the normal 'document' or 'domElement' context, the other works for custom events.

(overly) simplified usage would be something like this:
```js
// Normal use:
let transformControls = new TransformControls(camera, myCanvas);

// Worker use:
let transformControls = new TransformControls(camera, myController);

// Where myController is something like this:
class MyController extends EventEmitter
{
    constructor(myMouseDriver)
    {
        myMouseDriver.on('right-down', () => this.emit('mousedown', {button: 2});
        myMouseDriver.on('right-up', () => this.emit('mouseup', {button: 2});
        myMouseDriver.on('move', (x, y) => this.emit('mousemove', {x: x, y: y});
        // etc... (you probably want real function references so you can remove listeners again, but thats up to the developer implementing his/her own version of this controller.
    }
}
```

Meanwhile inside your code, there is something similar to this but one that works for DOM event listeners like you do it now with the part that describes the following:
```js
domElement.addEventListener( "mousedown", onPointerDown, false );
domElement.addEventListener( "touchstart", onPointerDown, false );
domElement.addEventListener( "mousemove", onPointerHover, false );
domElement.addEventListener( "touchmove", onPointerHover, false );
// etc..
```

So that would look like something like this:
```js
class DefaultInputController extends EventEmitter
{
    constructor(domElement)
    {
        let domElement = domElement || document;

        domElement.addEventListener( "mousedown", this.handleMouseDown);
    }

    handleMouseDown(event)
    {
        this.emit('mousedown', {button: 2}); // Note how this signature is the exact same as the one in "MyController".
    }
}
```

So the constructor of `TransformControls` would go from this:
```js
THREE.TransformControls = function ( camera, domElement ) {

        THREE.Object3D.call( this );

        domElement = ( domElement !== undefined ) ? domElement : document;
        // ...
}
```

to this:
```js
THREE.TransformControls = function ( camera, domElementOrController ) {

        THREE.Object3D.call( this );
        
        if (domElementOrController === undefined) {
            inputController = new DefaultInputController(document);
        } else if (typeof HTMLElement !== 'undefined' && domElementOrController instanceof HTMLElement) {
            inputController = new DefaultInputController(domElementOrController);
        } else {
            inputController = domElementOrController;
        }

        // ...
        // ...

        inputController.on('mousemove', this.pointerDown);

        // ...

        this.pointerDown = function (pointer) {
            let x = pointer.x,
                 y = pointer.y; 
            // No matter what input controller you choose, the way it works remains the same.
        }
}
```

Merely replacing the old `TransformControls` with the new one breaks OrbitControls and Raycaster in my app. I can no longer Raycast (click things) succesfully, or orbit the camera. I can still zoom though.

This is the only thing I'm doing with TransformControls:

```js
	initTransformControls(): void {
		this.transformControls = new TransformControls(this.state.camera, this.state.renderer.domElement)

		new AnnotatedSceneActions().addObjectToScene(this.transformControls)

		this.transformControls.addEventListener('change', () => {

			// we transformed something, the scene needs to be redrawn
			this.renderScene()

			// If we are interacting with the transform object don't hide it.
			this.cancelHideTransform()
		})

		// If we just clicked on a transform object don't hide it.
		this.transformControls.addEventListener('mouseDown', this.cancelHideTransform)

		// If we are done interacting with a transform object start hiding process.
		this.transformControls.addEventListener('mouseUp', this.delayHideTransform)

		// If the object attached to the transform object has changed, do something.
		this.transformControls.addEventListener('objectChange', () => this.props.channel.emit('transformUpdate'))
	}
```

where `renderScene` just calls `renderer.render`, and `cancelHideTransform` delays a call to `transformControls.detach()`. Otherwise, the only other call I ever make is `transformControls.attach(obj)`.

So somehow, swapping the TransformControls implementation in my app messes with OrbitControls and Raycasting.

What's `TransformControls` doing to the `camera` or the `domElement` that could mess up external classes like `OrbitControls` or `Raycaster`?
